# Java: Classes <a name="Classes" id="Classes"></a>

### Annotations <a name="Annotations" id="cdktf.Annotations"></a>

Includes API for attaching annotations such as warning messages to constructs.

#### Methods <a name="Methods" id="Methods"></a>

| **Name**                                                            | **Description**                                                    |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Annotations.addError">addError</a></code>     | Adds an { "error": < message > } metadata entry to this construct. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Annotations.addInfo">addInfo</a></code>       | Adds an info metadata entry to this construct.                     |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Annotations.addWarning">addWarning</a></code> | Adds a warning metadata entry to this construct.                   |

---

##### `addError` <a name="addError" id="cdktf.Annotations.addError"></a>

```java
public void addError(java.lang.String message)
```

Adds an { "error": < message > } metadata entry to this construct.

The toolkit will fail synthesis when errors are reported.

###### `message`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="message" id="cdktf.Annotations.addError.parameter.message"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

The error message.

---

##### `addInfo` <a name="addInfo" id="cdktf.Annotations.addInfo"></a>

```java
public void addInfo(java.lang.String message)
```

Adds an info metadata entry to this construct.

The CLI will display the info message when apps are synthesized.

###### `message`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="message" id="cdktf.Annotations.addInfo.parameter.message"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

The info message.

---

##### `addWarning` <a name="addWarning" id="cdktf.Annotations.addWarning"></a>

```java
public void addWarning(java.lang.String message)
```

Adds a warning metadata entry to this construct.

The CLI will display the warning when an app is synthesized.
In a future release the CLI might introduce a --strict flag which
will then fail the synthesis if it encounters a warning.

###### `message`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="message" id="cdktf.Annotations.addWarning.parameter.message"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

The warning message.

---

| **Name**                                            | **Description**                                    |
| --------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Annotations.of">of</a></code> | Returns the annotations API for a construct scope. |

---

##### `of` <a name="of" id="cdktf.Annotations.of"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Annotations;

Annotations.of(IConstruct scope)
```

Returns the annotations API for a construct scope.

###### `scope`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="scope" id="cdktf.Annotations.of.parameter.scope"></a>

- _Type:_ software.constructs.IConstruct

##### `dynamic` <a name="dynamic" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.dynamic"></a>

```java
public IResolvable dynamic(java.util.Map< java.lang.String, java.lang.Object > attributes)
```

###### `attributes`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="attributes" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.dynamic.parameter.attributes"></a>

##### `forExpressionForList` <a name="forExpressionForList" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForList(java.lang.String OR IResolvable expression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `forExpressionForMap` <a name="forExpressionForMap" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForMap(java.lang.String OR IResolvable keyExpression, java.lang.String OR IResolvable valueExpression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `keyExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="keyExpression" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `valueExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="valueExpression" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

##### `fromComplexList` <a name="fromComplexList" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator;

DynamicListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList(IResolvable OR ComplexList OR StringMapList OR NumberMapList OR BooleanMapList OR AnyMapList list, java.lang.String mapKeyAttributeName)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```java
// Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
Object cert = AcmCertificate.Builder.create(this, "cert")
        .domainName("example.com")
        .validationMethod("DNS")
        .build();

Object dvoIterator = TerraformIterator.fromComplexList(cert.getDomainValidationOptions(), "domain_name");

Route53Record.Builder.create(this, "record")
        .allowOverwrite(true)
        .name(dvoIterator.getString("name"))
        .records(List.of(dvoIterator.getString("record")))
        .ttl(60)
        .type(dvoIterator.getString("type"))
        .zoneId(Token.asString(dataAwsRoute53ZoneExample.getZoneId()))
        .forEach(dvoIterator)
        .build();
```

###### `list`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="list" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.list"></a>

##### `abs` <a name="abs" id="cdktf.Fn.abs"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Fn;

Fn.abs(java.lang.Number num)
```

{@link https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/functions/abs abs} returns the absolute value of the given number. In other words, if the number is zero or positive then it is returned as-is, but if it is negative then it is multiplied by -1 to make it positive before returning it.

###### `num`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="num" id="cdktf.Fn.abs.parameter.num"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.Number

---

##### `abspath` <a name="abspath" id="cdktf.Fn.abspath"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Fn;

Fn.abspath(java.lang.String path)
```

{@link https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/functions/abspath abspath} takes a string containing a filesystem path and converts it to an absolute path. That is, if the path is not absolute, it will be joined with the current working directory.

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

##### `abs` <a name="abs" id="cdktf.FnGenerated.abs"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.FnGenerated;

FnGenerated.abs(java.lang.Number num)
```

{@link https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/functions/abs abs} returns the absolute value of the given number. In other words, if the number is zero or positive then it is returned as-is, but if it is negative then it is multiplied by -1 to make it positive before returning it.

###### `num`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="num" id="cdktf.FnGenerated.abs.parameter.num"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.Number

### Lazy <a name="Lazy" id="cdktf.Lazy"></a>

Lazily produce a value.

Can be used to return a string, list or numeric value whose actual value
will only be calculated later, during synthesis.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.Lazy.Initializer"></a>

##### `forExpressionForList` <a name="forExpressionForList" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForList(java.lang.String OR IResolvable expression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `forExpressionForMap` <a name="forExpressionForMap" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForMap(java.lang.String OR IResolvable keyExpression, java.lang.String OR IResolvable valueExpression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `keyExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="keyExpression" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `valueExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="valueExpression" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

##### `fromComplexList` <a name="fromComplexList" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.ListTerraformIterator;

ListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList(IResolvable OR ComplexList OR StringMapList OR NumberMapList OR BooleanMapList OR AnyMapList list, java.lang.String mapKeyAttributeName)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```java
// Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
Object cert = AcmCertificate.Builder.create(this, "cert")
        .domainName("example.com")
        .validationMethod("DNS")
        .build();

Object dvoIterator = TerraformIterator.fromComplexList(cert.getDomainValidationOptions(), "domain_name");

Route53Record.Builder.create(this, "record")
        .allowOverwrite(true)
        .name(dvoIterator.getString("name"))
        .records(List.of(dvoIterator.getString("record")))
        .ttl(60)
        .type(dvoIterator.getString("type"))
        .zoneId(Token.asString(dataAwsRoute53ZoneExample.getZoneId()))
        .forEach(dvoIterator)
        .build();
```

###### `list`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="list" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.list"></a>

- _Type:_ <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.ComplexList">ComplexList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.StringMapList">StringMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.NumberMapList">NumberMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.BooleanMapList">BooleanMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.AnyMapList">AnyMapList</a>

the list to iterate over.

---

###### `mapKeyAttributeName`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="mapKeyAttributeName" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.mapKeyAttributeName"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

the name of the attribute that should be used as the key in the map.

Visit https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-on-complex-lists for more information.

---

##### `fromDataSources` <a name="fromDataSources" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.fromDataSources"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.ListTerraformIterator;

ListTerraformIterator.fromDataSources(ITerraformResource resource)
```

Creates a new iterator from a data source that has been created with the `for_each` argument.

###### `resource`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="resource" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.fromDataSources.parameter.resource"></a>

##### `dynamic` <a name="dynamic" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.dynamic"></a>

```java
public IResolvable dynamic(java.util.Map< java.lang.String, java.lang.Object > attributes)
```

Creates a dynamic expression that can be used to loop over this iterator in a dynamic block.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.
See https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-for-list-attributes

##### `forExpressionForList` <a name="forExpressionForList" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForList(java.lang.String OR IResolvable expression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `forExpressionForMap` <a name="forExpressionForMap" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForMap(java.lang.String OR IResolvable keyExpression, java.lang.String OR IResolvable valueExpression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `keyExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="keyExpression" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `valueExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="valueExpression" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

---

##### `keys` <a name="keys" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.keys"></a>

```java
public IResolvable keys()
```

Creates a for expression that maps the iterators to its keys.

For lists these would be the indices, for maps the keys.
As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

##### `pluckProperty` <a name="pluckProperty" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.pluckProperty"></a>

```java
public IResolvable pluckProperty(java.lang.String property)
```

Creates a for expression that accesses the key on each element of the iterator.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `property`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="property" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.pluckProperty.parameter.property"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

The property of the iterators values to map to.

---

##### `values` <a name="values" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.values"></a>

```java
public IResolvable values()
```

Creates a for expression that maps the iterators to its value in case it is a map.

For lists these would stay the same.
As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

##### `fromComplexList` <a name="fromComplexList" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.MapTerraformIterator;

MapTerraformIterator.fromComplexList(IResolvable OR ComplexList OR StringMapList OR NumberMapList OR BooleanMapList OR AnyMapList list, java.lang.String mapKeyAttributeName)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```java
// Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
Object cert = AcmCertificate.Builder.create(this, "cert")
        .domainName("example.com")
        .validationMethod("DNS")
        .build();

Object dvoIterator = TerraformIterator.fromComplexList(cert.getDomainValidationOptions(), "domain_name");

Route53Record.Builder.create(this, "record")
        .allowOverwrite(true)
        .name(dvoIterator.getString("name"))
        .records(List.of(dvoIterator.getString("record")))
        .ttl(60)
        .type(dvoIterator.getString("type"))
        .zoneId(Token.asString(dataAwsRoute53ZoneExample.getZoneId()))
        .forEach(dvoIterator)
        .build();
```

###### `list`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="list" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.list"></a>

- _Type:_ <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.ComplexList">ComplexList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.StringMapList">StringMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.NumberMapList">NumberMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.BooleanMapList">BooleanMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.AnyMapList">AnyMapList</a>

the list to iterate over.

---

###### `mapKeyAttributeName`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="mapKeyAttributeName" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.mapKeyAttributeName"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

the name of the attribute that should be used as the key in the map.

Visit https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-on-complex-lists for more information.

---

##### `dynamic` <a name="dynamic" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.dynamic"></a>

```java
public IResolvable dynamic(java.util.Map< java.lang.String, java.lang.Object > attributes)
```

Creates a dynamic expression that can be used to loop over this iterator in a dynamic block.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.
See https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-for-list-attributes

###### `attributes`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="attributes" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.dynamic.parameter.attributes"></a>

- _Type:_ java.util.Map< java.lang.String, java.lang.Object >

---

##### `forExpressionForList` <a name="forExpressionForList" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForList(java.lang.String OR IResolvable expression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `forExpressionForMap` <a name="forExpressionForMap" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForMap(java.lang.String OR IResolvable keyExpression, java.lang.String OR IResolvable valueExpression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `keyExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="keyExpression" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `valueExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="valueExpression" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

---

##### `getAny` <a name="getAny" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.getAny"></a>


##### `keys` <a name="keys" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.keys"></a>

```java
public IResolvable keys()
```

Creates a for expression that maps the iterators to its keys.

For lists these would be the indices, for maps the keys.
As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

##### `pluckProperty` <a name="pluckProperty" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.pluckProperty"></a>

```java
public IResolvable pluckProperty(java.lang.String property)
```

Creates a for expression that accesses the key on each element of the iterator.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `property`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="property" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.pluckProperty.parameter.property"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

The property of the iterators values to map to.

---

##### `values` <a name="values" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.values"></a>

```java
public IResolvable values()
```

Creates a for expression that maps the iterators to its value in case it is a map.

For lists these would stay the same.
As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

##### `fromComplexList` <a name="fromComplexList" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator;

ResourceTerraformIterator.fromComplexList(IResolvable OR ComplexList OR StringMapList OR NumberMapList OR BooleanMapList OR AnyMapList list, java.lang.String mapKeyAttributeName)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```java
// Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
Object cert = AcmCertificate.Builder.create(this, "cert")
        .domainName("example.com")
        .validationMethod("DNS")
        .build();

Object dvoIterator = TerraformIterator.fromComplexList(cert.getDomainValidationOptions(), "domain_name");

Route53Record.Builder.create(this, "record")
        .allowOverwrite(true)
        .name(dvoIterator.getString("name"))
        .records(List.of(dvoIterator.getString("record")))
        .ttl(60)
        .type(dvoIterator.getString("type"))
        .zoneId(Token.asString(dataAwsRoute53ZoneExample.getZoneId()))
        .forEach(dvoIterator)
        .build();
```

###### `list`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="list" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.list"></a>

- _Type:_ <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.ComplexList">ComplexList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.StringMapList">StringMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.NumberMapList">NumberMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.BooleanMapList">BooleanMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.AnyMapList">AnyMapList</a>

the list to iterate over.

---

###### `mapKeyAttributeName`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="mapKeyAttributeName" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.mapKeyAttributeName"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

the name of the attribute that should be used as the key in the map.

Visit https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-on-complex-lists for more information.

---

### TaggedCloudWorkspaces <a name="TaggedCloudWorkspaces" id="cdktf.TaggedCloudWorkspaces"></a>

A set of Terraform Cloud workspace tags.

You will be able to use this working directory with any workspaces that have all of the specified tags, and can use the terraform workspace commands to switch between them or create new workspaces. New workspaces will automatically have the specified tags. This option conflicts with name.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.TaggedCloudWorkspaces.Initializer"></a>

##### `dynamic` <a name="dynamic" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.dynamic"></a>

```java
public IResolvable dynamic(java.util.Map< java.lang.String, java.lang.Object > attributes)
```

Creates a dynamic expression that can be used to loop over this iterator in a dynamic block.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.
See https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-for-list-attributes

###### `attributes`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="attributes" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.dynamic.parameter.attributes"></a>

- _Type:_ java.util.Map< java.lang.String, java.lang.Object >

---

##### `forExpressionForList` <a name="forExpressionForList" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForList(java.lang.String OR IResolvable expression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `forExpressionForMap` <a name="forExpressionForMap" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```java
public IResolvable forExpressionForMap(java.lang.String OR IResolvable keyExpression, java.lang.String OR IResolvable valueExpression)
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `keyExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="keyExpression" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `valueExpression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="valueExpression" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String OR <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

---

##### `keys` <a name="keys" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.keys"></a>

```java
public IResolvable keys()
```

Creates a for expression that maps the iterators to its keys.

For lists these would be the indices, for maps the keys.
As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

##### `pluckProperty` <a name="pluckProperty" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.pluckProperty"></a>


##### `values` <a name="values" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.values"></a>

```java
public IResolvable values()
```

a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

##### `fromComplexList` <a name="fromComplexList" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.TerraformIterator;

TerraformIterator.fromComplexList(IResolvable OR ComplexList OR StringMapList OR NumberMapList OR BooleanMapList OR AnyMapList list, java.lang.String mapKeyAttributeName)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```java
// Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
Object cert = AcmCertificate.Builder.create(this, "cert")
        .domainName("example.com")
        .validationMethod("DNS")
        .build();

Object dvoIterator = TerraformIterator.fromComplexList(cert.getDomainValidationOptions(), "domain_name");

Route53Record.Builder.create(this, "record")
        .allowOverwrite(true)
        .name(dvoIterator.getString("name"))
        .records(List.of(dvoIterator.getString("record")))
        .ttl(60)
        .type(dvoIterator.getString("type"))
        .zoneId(Token.asString(dataAwsRoute53ZoneExample.getZoneId()))
        .forEach(dvoIterator)
        .build();
```

###### `list`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="list" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.list"></a>

- _Type:_ <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.ComplexList">ComplexList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.StringMapList">StringMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.NumberMapList">NumberMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.BooleanMapList">BooleanMapList</a> OR <a href="#cdktf.AnyMapList">AnyMapList</a>

the list to iterate over.

---

###### `mapKeyAttributeName`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="mapKeyAttributeName" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.mapKeyAttributeName"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.String

the name of the attribute that should be used as the key in the map.

Visit https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-on-complex-lists for more information.

---

### TerraformSelf <a name="TerraformSelf" id="cdktf.TerraformSelf"></a>

Expressions in connection blocks cannot refer to their parent resource by name.

References create dependencies, and referring to a resource by name within its own block would create a dependency cycle.
Instead, expressions can use the self object, which represents the connection's parent resource and has all of that resource's attributes.
For example, use self.public_ip to reference an aws_instance's public_ip attribute.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.TerraformSelf.Initializer"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.TerraformSelf;

new TerraformSelf();
```

| **Name** | **Type** | **Description** |
| -------- | -------- | --------------- |

---

#### Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>

| **Name**                                                            | **Description**                                                                     |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformSelf.getAny">getAny</a></code>       | Only usable within a connection block to reference the connections parent resource. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformSelf.getNumber">getNumber</a></code> | Only usable within a connection block to reference the connections parent resource. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformSelf.getString">getString</a></code> | Only usable within a connection block to reference the connections parent resource. |

---

##### `getAny` <a name="getAny" id="cdktf.TerraformSelf.getAny"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.TerraformSelf;

TerraformSelf.getAny(java.lang.String key)
```

Only usable within a connection block to reference the connections parent resource.

Access a property on the resource like this: `getAny("hostPort")`

###### `key`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="key" id="cdktf.TerraformSelf.getAny.parameter.key"></a>

### Token <a name="Token" id="cdktf.Token"></a>

Represents a special or lazily-evaluated value.

Can be used to delay evaluation of a certain value in case, for example,
that it requires some context or late-bound data. Can also be used to
mark values that need special processing at document rendering time.

Tokens can be embedded into strings while retaining their original
semantics.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.Token.Initializer"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Token;

new Token();
```

| **Name** | **Type** | **Description** |
| -------- | -------- | --------------- |

---

#### Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>

| **Name**                                                          | **Description**                                          |
| ----------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asAny">asAny</a></code>               | Return a resolvable representation of the given value.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asAnyMap">asAnyMap</a></code>         | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asBooleanMap">asBooleanMap</a></code> | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asList">asList</a></code>             | Return a reversible list representation of this token.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asMap">asMap</a></code>               | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asNumber">asNumber</a></code>         | Return a reversible number representation of this token. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asNumberList">asNumberList</a></code> | Return a reversible list representation of this token.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asNumberMap">asNumberMap</a></code>   | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asString">asString</a></code>         | Return a reversible string representation of this token. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asStringMap">asStringMap</a></code>   | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.isUnresolved">isUnresolved</a></code> | Returns true if obj represents an unresolved value.      |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.nullValue">nullValue</a></code>       | Return a Token containing a `null` value.                |

##### `asString` <a name="asString" id="cdktf.Token.asString"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Token;

Token.asString(java.lang.Object value),Token.asString(java.lang.Object value, EncodingOptions options)
```

Return a reversible string representation of this token.

If the Token is initialized with a literal, the stringified value of the
literal is returned. Otherwise, a special quoted string representation
of the Token is returned that can be embedded into other strings.

Strings with quoted Tokens in them can be restored back into
complex values with the Tokens restored by calling `resolve()`
on the string.

###### `value`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value" id="cdktf.Token.asString.parameter.value"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.Object

---

###### `options`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="options" id="cdktf.Token.asString.parameter.options"></a>

- _Type:_ <a href="#cdktf.EncodingOptions">EncodingOptions</a>

---

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Token;

Token.asStringMap(java.lang.Object value),Token.asStringMap(java.lang.Object value, EncodingOptions options)
```

Return a reversible map representation of this token.

###### `value`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value" id="cdktf.Token.asStringMap.parameter.value"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.Object

---

###### `options`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="options" id="cdktf.Token.asStringMap.parameter.options"></a>

##### `isUnresolved` <a name="isUnresolved" id="cdktf.Token.isUnresolved"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Token;

Token.isUnresolved(java.lang.Object obj)
```

Returns true if obj represents an unresolved value.

One of these must be true:

- `obj` is an IResolvable
- `obj` is a string containing at least one encoded `IResolvable`
- `obj` is either an encoded number or list

This does NOT recurse into lists or objects to see if they
containing resolvables.

###### `obj`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="obj" id="cdktf.Token.isUnresolved.parameter.obj"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.Object

The object to test.

---

##### `nullValue` <a name="nullValue" id="cdktf.Token.nullValue"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Token;

Token.nullValue()
```

Return a Token containing a `null` value.

Note: This is different than `undefined`, `nil`, `None` or similar
as it will end up in the Terraform config and can be used to explicitly
not set an attribute (which is sometimes required by Terraform providers)

#### Constants <a name="Constants" id="Constants"></a>

| **Name**                                                                                       | **Type**                      | **Description**                        |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.property.ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE">ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE</a></code>       | <code>java.lang.String</code> | Any map token representation.          |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.property.NUMBER_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE">NUMBER_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE</a></code> | <code>java.lang.Number</code> | Number Map token value representation. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.property.STRING_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE">STRING_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE</a></code> | <code>java.lang.String</code> | String Map token value representation. |

---

##### `ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE" id="cdktf.Token.property.ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE"></a>

| **Name**                                                                           | **Description**                                                                                    |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Tokenization.isResolvable">isResolvable</a></code>           | Return whether the given object is an IResolvable object.                                          |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Tokenization.resolve">resolve</a></code>                     | Resolves an object by evaluating all tokens and removing any undefined or empty objects or arrays. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Tokenization.reverse">reverse</a></code>                     | Reverse any value into Resolvables, if possible.                                                   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Tokenization.reverseList">reverseList</a></code>             | Un-encode a Tokenized value from a list.                                                           |

| <code><a href="#cdktf.Tokenization.stringifyNumber">stringifyNumber</a></code>     | Stringify a number directly or lazily if it's a Token.                                             |

##### `isResolvable` <a name="isResolvable" id="cdktf.Tokenization.isResolvable"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Tokenization;

Tokenization.isResolvable(java.lang.Object obj)
```

Return whether the given object is an IResolvable object.

This is different from Token.isUnresolved() which will also check for
encoded Tokens, whereas this method will only do a type check on the given
object.

###### `obj`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="obj" id="cdktf.Tokenization.isResolvable.parameter.obj"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.Object

---

##### `resolve` <a name="resolve" id="cdktf.Tokenization.resolve"></a>

```java
import com.hashicorp.cdktf.Tokenization;

Tokenization.resolve(java.lang.Object obj, ResolveOptions options)
```

Resolves an object by evaluating all tokens and removing any undefined or empty objects or arrays.

Values can only be primitives, arrays or tokens. Other objects (i.e. with methods) will be rejected.

###### `obj`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="obj" id="cdktf.Tokenization.resolve.parameter.obj"></a>

- _Type:_ java.lang.Object

The object to resolve.

---

###### `options`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="options" id="cdktf.Tokenization.resolve.parameter.options"></a>

- _Type:_ <a href="#cdktf.ResolveOptions">ResolveOptions</a>

Prefix key path components for diagnostics.
